Cholesterol is a type of lipid that facilitates the formation of coronary artery disease, atherosclerosis, myocardial infarctions, 
strokes, and more. Having an unusually high cholesterol of more than 240 mg/dl can increase the risk of experiencing such diseases. 
Understanding which populations tend to have the highest average amount of cholesterol is important, for it can guide healthcare 
professionals in preventing and treating cholesterol-caused diseases. This comparative analysis analyzes the trends of cholesterol 
among various demographic subgroups, drawing on published NHANES data from the CDC.

It is shown that Asians (190.93 mg/dl), Older Adults (195.94 mg/dl), and Females (190.47 mg/dl) have the highest cholesterol, on 
average, in their respective subgroups. Statistical analysis shows that different age groups have distinctly different cholesterol 
levels, whereas different races and ethnicities tend to have the same cholesterol level of 187.3 mg/dl, which matches established 
records of average cholesterol level. No single group has a cholesterol level above 200 mg/dl, but older adults are, on average, more 
likely to experience a risk of 200+ cholesterol levels. It is also shown that cholesterol rises with age and, after peaking in the 
older adult range, falls with gentrification due to age related weight loss and a slowing metabolism; conversely, it rises until that 
point due to a weakening liver in the human body. 
